Read, and periodically review, the owner's manual to make use of your camera's features such as ASA, macro, forced flash, auto, night etc. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Move around or about. Also try pictures from a low or high vantage point. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Take shots with normal, wide angle and telephoto. Use wide angle to include the desired elements into the frame. Use telephoto to simplify a picture. "Telephoto" is commonly used to access the subject otherwise not possible - such as in an event where you are not allowed to get closer. Telephoto is also used to make a person look thinner. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Review the basics themes of composition before a photo shoot: c and s curves, contrast, diagonal and horizontal line uses, subject matter, patterns, the way the eyes move throughout the picture when viewing it, aesthetics, texture, framing, taking an interesting photo and texture. Also mentally review the technical aspects of photography. Make a checklist of equipment for your photo shoot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/05/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/05/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

After a photo shoot transfer the pictures to your computer and delete them from your camera. Delete those few pictures that were technically very bad, otherwise save most of your picture and back them up on on a portable hard drive or online. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b3/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Edit your photos and look for "gems" within a photo. It is important to take a technically good photo and a camera with good resolution, so you can crop and develop those gems. Spend as much time and energy in editing as in composing pictures with your camera. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet6.jpg/v4-460px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet6.jpg/v4-760px-Compose-Photos-Step-1Bullet6.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":505.27472527472526,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
